How VAR can get it that wrong on Liverpool's denied goal is shameful. They said they saw there was no offside but validated the on-field decision by saying 'check over' (although the linesman had raised his flag so wouldn't the on-field decision be 'no-goal') and the ref interpreted the 'check over' as 'offside'. Then when the game starts again supposedly VAR cannot do anything? Really? Don't they talk to the ref? Couldn't they have simply said, when they saw the ref give a freekick for offside: "No mate, we meant there is no offside you may award the goal?" So embarrassing!

On the Disallowed Goal...  As much as this a human error, it is not an individual official's error. If we take the emotion out of this and spare the poor officials - this is a simple problem and has a simple solution. Challenge me on this.  ---Problem is in the process: Taking this particular instance as an example: A particular decision was being checked by VAR.  It is open to interpretation whether... - the OFFSIDE was being checked or  - the GOAL was being checked  What was actually shown on the screen - 'Checking for Disallowed GOAL - Offside'  Ultimately, the decision relayed was CHECK COMPLETE.  Hence, depending on what you thought was being checked, you could interpret the decision accordingly as well.  ------- ---The 100 million $ Solution: ------- VAR officials to show the ultimate decision post the VAR check... in the below format  Ultimate decision (Reason)  GOAL stays (Not offside) Or GOAL Disallowed (Offside)  The above to be vetted by both 1st and 2nd VAR officials before the decision is displayed.  These kind of things take time and should be allowed adequate time. Time to be taken on average by VAR (provided the right angles and pictures are available on the spot to the officials) -1st VAR official to make decisions - 20 seconds (max) -2nd VAR official to review decision - 10 seconds (max) Allow for a 10 second consultaion, at the end, with the onfield referee. Total time taken - 40 seconds (max)  Possible other improvements suggested: - Allow for VAR audio to be available, to make things more transparent   What say Spurs???

Liverpool fought well, but in the end the result was right and hard to give a performance with 9 Players on the field, apart from the VAR mistakes...."AGAIN".  Unlucky with that first booking, which led to a second booking and that sending off, nothing wrong with the Jones sending off, if Gusto was sent off for what he did, this one was identical and I and others would have been annoyed if he had not been, then there was the goal that should have stood.  Week in and week out, mistakes by a VAR Team.  Not just subtle mistakes, but ruddy great glaring ones.  There is nothing wrong with VAR, it works perfectly.  It is the Monkeys in charge of it, that is the problem and always will be until they do something about it.  You begin to wonder if they are being paid off by whoever, the mistakes are so blatant.  Then you get, "Ooops! Yes, sorry, mistake was made" and yet nothing is done.  No answering for that mistake, no punishment and it really is not good enough.  We had an incident just the other week, where a VAR Official played "The Old Pals Act", admitted it and nothing was done about that either.  How much longer are we, the Fans, the Players, Managers, Clubs supposed to put up with this incompetence, before something is REALLY done.  Once again VAR Officials spoiled a really good game.

Ok, I see you Liverpool fans being mad at this situation for Luis Diaz's goal being offside, as a spurs fan watching the match live, I also thought it was a clear onside. Also, the red for Diogo Jota should not have been stood, since the first yellow card was not reasonable. But as a spurs fan, the first red was a clear red, which could have made Bissouma in a big injury. So, if it was to say liverpool got the first goal and there was only one red card, I think we would have still won the match, since when liverpool were down to 9 men, all 9 men went down defending to keep the tie, that's why spurs struggled until the last minute of OG to win the game, but if liverpool had 10 men they would have kept the attacking position which could have lead spurs for an more easier attacking stance against liverpool defense, which in my thought could have lead to more goals maybe 3:1. Finally, liverpool fans, even though it was a controversy win, we won, and it is not the player's or the fans fault, it is the referee's so go blame them, and also remember the last minute goal was an own goal by your own player.

All the debate around the whole thing with the VAR calls is a bit silly.  Humans have a well documented habit of attributing important reasons to things with important outcomes. We’ll speculate about prominent assassinations for centuries or longer, but hardly bother thinking about all attempted assassinations that don’t amount to much. We have a hard time accepting that things that feel important happen for random reasons. It makes us feel insignificant and not in control.  In the mind of the liverpool fan, there’s either a conspiracy, or they got robbed by a flukey bad day at the office from the VAR officials. One of those feels more satisfying. One of those is easier for folks to swallow. But it being easier to believe and more soothing to the psyche doesn’t mean that it’s a take with any particular bearing in reality.  The backlash is exclusively because of the perception that this ‘changed’ a result. And the increased speculation too. Personally, I think that Allison had a ridiculous game and Liverpool are lucky to not have given up 4 or 5. If the final score line was 5-1, the discussion would be very different.

I am only speculating but, I wonder if the Luis Diaz "offside" goal had really been allowed whether the flow of the game and the ultimate scoreline outcome would have been different than it turned out. Whenever one team scores, what often happens is that the team that has been scored upon has to eventually decide to play more purposefully with the aim of trying to even the score, if they initially fail to equalise without upping the tempo of their game. I know that Spurs has come from behind on many an occasion this season, but typically when a team does have to play catch-up football and purposefully up their own tempo, it has the potential of creating space on the field thereby making the game more open and as a consequence, the team who does this becomes more vulnerable to the opposition's counter-attack, which is something you do not want to see happen with Liverpool's pace up front.

Tottenham was extremely lucky today, having the refs with them and seeing Liverpool being robbed of a goal and being reduced to 9 men. Wrong team won, I think one has to be completely biased not to agree on that. What it concerns the refs, they were suitably dressed in black as grave diggers should be. They buried the game for us in a way I lack words to explain. I have rarely seen such a one sided focus from these referees who were so obviously not up to the task. For the ref just brush off Garcia's goal as offside without a proper look at the situation, makes him a hazard to have on a pitch. My absolute feeling is that he wouldn't dare to take such a sloppy decision in front of the Kop. The man hasn't the necessary courage to be ignorant of the press an audience like Anfield has. My point is that this crew of refs had judged things differently on Anfield. It's a damned shame that having the referees deciding the outcome of a match. No one can't claim that it's what happened. The way Tottenham celebrated our unlucky self goal in the dying minutes of the game, show also that this was the only way they could luck up our defense. Since they couldn't do their defender man to man, they were never able to get behind our line of superb defense. They needed a lucky strike and they got it. As a Liverpool fan with some of the European nights behind us, I would be the last man denying that luck has nothing to do with it. Of course it has. Sometimes you need a goal like Tottenham got, even if it was against 9 man. But it was how Liverpool went down to 9 men that's the interesting point here. I have seen brutal, brutal games between Chelsea and Liverpool or Barca and Real Madrid and no one has been given the red card. Football is a contact sport. Let the gravediggers take that aspect of the game away and you end up with 2-1 to Tottenham. 🇸🇪❤️🔴👍🆗

왜 팀의 수비가 망가졌는지 아시나요? 근본적인 이유를 알려드리죠. 결론부터 말씀드리면 페리시치와 포로라는 2명의 수비력이 없는 윙백 2명때문에 벌어진 사태죠.  페리시치와 포로같은 윙백때문에 분명히 코치진들이 센터백들에게 윙백들이 수비력이 부족하니까 여유가 되는 상황에서는 그 윙백들 수비를 좀 같이 도와줘라고 말했을겁니다.   (다이어 같은 센터백들은 원래 수비실력이 않좋았던것도 있지만)  수비수들은 무엇보다 가장 합리적이고 더 나은 판단을 빨리 내리는게 중요합니다. 즉 예를들어 내가 저쪽애를 마크하러 가는게 낫겠구나 그러면 이쪽상대를 내옆 동료가 마크하는게 나을거니까 라는식의 판단을 빨리 하고 실행을 하죠. 그런데...기존의 일반적인 수비방식이 아닌....우리팀에 수비수중에 수비력이 안돼는 수비수가 2명이 생기면서 그 윙백 2명이 각자 마크해야할 상대선수까지 여차하면 도와줘야하는데...다른정상적인 팀이라면 이런일은 벌어지지 않는거죠.. 우리팀만 현재 윙백이 있는데 그 윙백은 수비력이 0에 가까우니까요. 그래서 그 윙백이 혹시 뚫리면 도와주러 가는 경우까지 생각해야하게 되죠. 그래서 판단을 하는데 있어서 더 복잡해지고 그래서 생각하는데 시간이 더 걸리기도 하고 잘못된 판단을 하게되기도 할껍니다.  또는 코치진이 그렇게 오더를 하진 않았을지라도 센터백들이 윙백들의 수비실력을 믿지 못하게 되서 결국 그런 경우까지 대비하고 고려해서 판단을 하게 됬을지도 모릅니다.  그래서 결국엔 센터백 1명이 이런일을 계속하다보니 계속 문제가 생기고 또 다른 센터백도 이 센터백을 신뢰할수가 없게 되고 또 반복되는 문제가 생기게 되죠.  또한 이 윙백들이 수비또한 잘 하지도 않기도 하고 수비실력도 없어서 윙포워드들 또한 망가지고 있죠. 윙포워드들이 이 윙백이 공격하러 자리를 비우면 그거 백업하느라 더욱 수비쪽으로 위치하게 됩니다. 그래서 공격하러 올라가는 거리가 길어지게되고 더욱 지치게 됩니다. 그래서 공격수가 공격포인트가 별로 없게 된다고 사람들로 부터 비난을 받게되고 그로인해 공격을 하러올라갔을때 평정심을 잃고 좀더 욕심을 부리게 되어 무리한 슈팅을 나사하게 되기도 합니다.   즉 이렇게 윙백을 위한 축구를 하던 콘테 하나때문에 팀전체가 무너진거죠..  이에대한 증빙자료가 될만한 사실로는 페리시치가 영입되기 전까지는 수비조직력이 괜찮아서 전시즌 후반기때는 성적도 잘나와서 탑4에 들어 챔스도 나가게됬죠. 그런데 같은 센터백선수인데...페리시치가 영입된 이번시즌 부터는 수비조직력이 30퍼센트정도 하락했죠.  실점 상황을 보면 알수있죠. 그리고 올 겨울 포로가 영입되고나서는 수비조직력이 60퍼센트까지 더 하락하게되고 실점은 더욱 늘어나게 됩니다.  즉 수비력없는 윙백(페리시치)이 1명 생겼을땐 실점이 30퍼센트 늘었고 수비력없는 윙백(포로)이 1명 더 생기니까 실점이 60퍼센트인 2배로 더 늘었죠. 양쪽다 수비력없는 윙백이 출전해버리니까 수비조직력이 완전 막장이 되어버린거죠.  윙백은 수비는 할줄 모르는데 그렇다고 공격을 공격수보다 잘하는것도 아니고...도데체 이런 비효율적인 짓을 왜 콘테는 한겁니까.  즉 콘테는 공격이 전문인 공격수들에겐 수비를 시키고, 공격이 전문이 아닌선수들에게 공격을 시켰죠. 얼마나 비효율적이냐구요.  다음시즌엔 이런 폐단을 없애려면... 페리시치와 포로 같은 윙백은 팔아버려야합니다.  4백 시스템으로 정상적수비력을 갖춘 풀백을 영입하고 좋은감독 영입해야합니다

i don't think i've ever felt this way after any other match before. forget that southampton 3-3. forget all the losses in the cup competitions to small teams. forget the chamions league final. i don't know what it is, but this match left me completely emotionally destroyed. i don't know what to feel. i know this match doesn't hold much significance as we might not even make top 4 anyway. plus, i've already given up on this season. but for some reason, this is the most deflated i've ever been supporting tottenham. it was instant dissappointment after conceding three. then it was worrying about this game becoming another newcastle. then the building hope as we scored each goal. then it was the dreaming of a historic comeback at anfield. then it was absolute euphoria as richy scored. and just as i was still celebrating like mad, it was complete devastation. i literally felt the highest form of happiness and lowest form of sadness within a fcking minute. i feel like i've just let all my fcking emotions out and now i'm just empty. but in a very negative way. why lucas why

I have been away from sports and football for many years now. I use to watch them on television in the years 1998- to 2007, but it was not a lot. I use to keep up with the exploits of Ronaldo and Messi but never had time to watch full matches. Recently after the world cup I started watching on Youtube and found myself connecting with Brighton and Hove Albion and becoming their fans, but in the last couple of weeks I find myself increasingly watching more matches. As it was sunday I watched both Man C and Man U matches on my two computer screens simultaneously,While I enjoy Man C's play I do like all the other teams even the lower ones as all of them fight to survive. The relegation format and the English Premire legue is really one of the best in the world. As I wanted to know who will take the No. 5 spot I did watch the entire Liverpool vs Tottenham match as a 3rd party and boy if every there was a match that brings a past fanatic back to being one. The last minute of the game reminded me why I was the lone kid in my school in India watching English football matches while all the rest watched cricket or something else. Now I pretty much will end up watching almost all matches if I can or at least extended highlights. The "bug" was hovering over me, bet me and now has laid eggs in my brain.

If Liverpool wants to be a top contender next season , it will really need to do a complete rebuild and shakedown of the team , to “find themselves” again.  They are a far cry from the winning and championship capable team from the 2018/2019.      Man city is performing at such a proficient level , that nothing will be able to touch them as contenders, for the next couple of seasons.   In the past seasons , PL teams would be apprehensive about taking on liverpool , because of the superb consistency and also how well the team as a whole was clicking together so well like a super well oiled machine.  Now , they have no qualms or doubts about taking on the current Liverpool team.

Wolves fans, hear me out...I watched the cross about 30 times...at normal speed and at 0.5. I think Onana was looking at the ball and when the Wolves player collided with his teammate, he stayed in that place unexpectedly for Onana. I'm not saying it's never a penalty. It could've been a penalty. But it wasn't intentional, I think. Because, after the player heads it, why would Onana just foul him AFTER he heads the ball? What reason would he have to do that? He's not defending the ball. He's not preventing the player from heading the ball. It would be insane to assume that he just went for the player with his hands like that. You try to run, reach for the ball, collide with a player, even if it's your teammate, and not let your hand go forward like his did. Try it. You don't need an actual ball. Just run, jump, reach out and bump into someone...see where your hands go. Again, if the ref had called a penalty, I would've just thought it was unfortunate, but legitimate.   Onana was a little late...and that doesn't completely justify him, but it's a world of difference between being a little late and going for a player with intent. Just like Wan Bissaka was late with that tackle. That could've easily been a yellow card...but I understand why it wasn't. When you misjudge a situation, you're late and it results with tackling a player, it's not your fault, but it still happened....so yeah, it could've been a penalty, but I understand why it wasn't.   I'm not gonna listen to what pundits have to say, cause they're disgustingly partial and all wolves fans will say it was a penalty and all utd fans will say it wasn't. If you judge an situation only through the prism of your own interest....well, you're a bit of a bastard.
